Answering my own question:

* It isn&#39;t possible to have a solution that is completely non-blocking. Even `ScheduledThreadPoolExecutor` keeps at least one thread around waiting for the queue to return a new task.
* `ThreadPoolExecutor` sits on top of a `BlockingQueue`. When there are no tasks left, it blocks on `BlockingQueue.take()`
* The solution has 3 moving pieces:
1. A rate limiter.
2. A `BlockingQueue` that hides elements until the rate limiter allows their consumption.
3. A `ThreadPoolExecutor` that sits on top of the `BlockingQueue`.

The Rate Limiter
---
I provide my own rate limiter based on the [Token Bucket algorithm](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Token_bucket) algorithm to overcome `RateLimiter`&#39;s [limitations](https://stackoverflow.com/q/27711962/14731). The source-code can be found [here](https://github.com/cowwoc/token-bucket).

---

The BlockingQueue
---
I implementing a `BlockingDeque` (which extends `BlockingQueue`) because in the future I want to try pushing failed tasks back to the front of the queue.

RateLimitedBlockingDeque.java

